ff\u53ee\u5679\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Molly's Game]]'' \n| \u8309\u8389\u724c\u5c40\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Thunder Agents]]''<ref name=Frater/>\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' \n|\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mile 22]]'' \n|\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Peppermint (2018 film)|Peppermint]]'' \n|\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Happytime Murders]]'' \n|\n|\n|-\n|\n| ''untitled Horror film''\n|\n| (co-production with [[Silver Pictures]])<ref>https://variety.com/2017/film/news/hayes-brothers-joel-silver-horror-movie-1202632782/</ref>\n|}\n\n==Talent agency==\nHBMC manages over 100 Chinese A-list celebrities of movie, music and TV. [[Xun Zhou]], [[Angelababy]], [[Chen Kun (actor)|Kun Chen]], [[Zhao Wei]] and [[Shu Qi]] have appeared in Huayi productions.\n\n==See also==\n* [[C-pop]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://huayi.sina.com.cn/}} {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Film distributors of China}}\n{{Film production companies of China}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of mainland China]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Sibling filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of China]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Shenzhen Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of China]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of China]]\n[[Category:Cinemas and movie theaters in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Chinese entertainment and media conglomerate|the South Korean subsidiary|Huayi Brothers (South Korean company)}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = Huayi Brothers Media Corporation<br/>\u534e\u8c0a\u5144\u5f1f\u4f20\u5a92\u96c6\u56e2\n|logo             = Huayi Brothers Media.jpg\n|logo_size        = 200px\n|type             = Public ([[Shenzhen Stock Exchange|SZSE]]:300027)\n|genre            = \n|fate             = \n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|foundation       = 1994\n|founder          = [[Wang Zhongjun]], Wang Zhonglei\n|defunct          = \n|location_city    = [[Beijing]]\n|location_country = [[China]] \n|locations        = 1\n|key_people       = [[Wang Zhongjun]] (Chairman & [[CEO]]), Wang Zhonglei (President)\n|area_served      = China\n|industry         = {{nowrap|[[Entertainment]]}}\n|products         = Movies, television shows, music, movie theaters\n|services         = Talent representation for musicians and actors/actresses\n|revenue          = {{Increase}} CNY 892,000,000 (2011)\n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|aum              = \n|assets           = \n|equity           = \n|owner            = Wang Zhongjun, Wang Zhonglei\n|num_employees    = \n|parent           = \n|divisions        = \n|subsid           = Huayi Brothers Film Investment Co., Ltd.<br/>Huayi Brothers TV Service Co., Ltd.<br/>Huayi Brothers Contemporary Culture Broker Co., Ltd.<br/>Huayi Brothers Music Co., Ltd.<br/>Huayi Brothers Advertising Co., Ltd.<br/>Huayi Brothers International Distribution Ltd<br>[[Huayi Brothers Korea|Huayi Brothers Korea Co., Ltd.]]\n|homepage         = {{URL|http://huayimedia.com}}\n|footnotes        = \n}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Huayi Brothers\n| image       = \n| founded     = 1994\n| defunct     = \n| founder     = [[Wang Zhongjun]], Wang Zhonglei\n| distributor = \n| genre       = [[Mandopop]]\n| country     = [[China]]\n| location    = [[Beijing]], [[China]]\n| url         = {{URL|ent.sina.com.cn/huayi}}\n| image_bg    = \n}}\n\n'''Huayi Brothers Media Corp.''' ({{zh|s=\u534e\u8c0a\u5144\u5f1f\u4f20\u5a92\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|p=Hu\u00e1y\u00ec Xi\u014dngd\u00ec Chu\u00e1nm\u00e9i G\u01d4f\u00e8n Y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n G\u014dngs\u012b}}) is a Chinese multinational entertainment company that owns a [[film studio]], a television [[production company]], a [[talent agency]], a [[record label]], and a [[movie theater|movie theater chain]] founded in [[Beijing]] by brothers [[Wang Zhongjun]] and Wang Zhonglei in 1994. The company made world news on October 30, 2009 when the Shenzhen Stock Exchange [[ChiNext]] Board was halted, after HBMC's stock price reached 122.74 percent above its IPO price, to open at 63.66 yuan per share.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = All stocks trigger suspensions on China's Nasdaq-style board under price-rise rules on first day\n| url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90778/90859/6799005.html\n| accessdate = 12 June 2014}}</ref> Patrick Frater of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"China\u2019s largest private sector film conglomerate\".<ref name=Frater>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/huayi-brothers-michael-uslan-pact-for-thunder-agents-franchise-1201615725/|title= China\u2019s Huayi Brothers Sets Superhero Franchise Pact With Michael Uslan|author= Patrick Frater|date= October 12, 2015|accessdate= October 14, 2015|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref> In 2014, the company was the seventh-largest film distributor in China, with 2.26% of the market.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://english.entgroup.cn/uploads/reports/China%20Film%20Industry%20Report%202014-2015%EF%BC%88in%20brief%EF%BC%89.pdf|title= China Film Industry Report 2014-2015 (In Brief)|accessdate= October 15, 2015|work= english.entgroup.cn|publisher= EntGroup Inc}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded in 1994 as a film production company. It underwent a comprehensive expansion into the media industry through investing and now produces movies, TV shows, & music and operates a film studio, TV production company, a talent agency, a record label, and movie theaters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.trmusic.com.cn/intro/about.htm |title=www.trmusic.com.cn/intro/about.htm |access-date=2010-12-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901230544/http://www.trmusic.com.cn/intro/about.htm |archive-date=2011-09-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn February 2011, Huayi Brothers revealed their plans to create the largest TV and film studio complex in East Asia.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?huayi_brothers_to_build_east_asias_largest_film_and_tv_studio_complex_16432.aspx | title = Huayi Brothers to build East Asia's largest film and TV studio complex | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = 2011-02-24 | access-date = 2011-02-26 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140413131510/http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?huayi_brothers_to_build_east_asias_largest_film_and_tv_studio_complex_16432.aspx | archive-date = 2014-04-13 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Also, they announced that they aim to earn 10 billion yuan in the box office by 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?huayi_brothers_unveils_their_moneymaking_plan_16522.aspx | title = Huayi Brothers unveils their moneymaking plan | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = 2011-03-16 | access-date = 2011-03-28 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170826065207/http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?huayi_brothers_unveils_their_moneymaking_plan_16522.aspx | archive-date = 2017-08-26 | url-status = dead }}</ref> As of April 2015, the company was worth US$7.9 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/biz/asia/chinese-media-stocks-stage-major-rally-in-us-and-asian-markets-1201469237/|title= Chinese Media Stocks Stage Major Rally in U.S. and Asian Markets|author= Patrick Frater|date= April 9, 2015|accessdate= April 14, 2015|work=[[variety.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 the company announced that it had agreed to invest as much as $150 million in Studio 8, the production company launched by former [[Warner Bros.]] executive Jeff Robinov, but Shanghai-based conglomerate [[Fosun International]] later signed a deal to invest in Robinov's company instead.<ref>Verrier, Richard [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-china-broken-deals-20150906-story.html For Hollywood, the road to China is littered with broken deals] ''Los Angeles Times''. September 7, 2015</ref> The same year the company acquired 79% stake<ref>https://technology.ihs.com/511196/huayi-brothers-to-acquire-leading-stake-in-gdc-technology</ref><ref>https://variety.com/2014/biz/asia/chinas-huayi-to-pay-125-million-for-d-cinema-group-gdc-technology-1201307397/</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chinas-huayi-brothers-buys-controlling-733146</ref><ref>http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2014-09/17/content_18614620.htm</ref> in GDC Technology Limited, a ''[[Digital cinema|Digital Cinema]]'' solutions provider,  which was held by private equity funds ''[[The Carlyle Group|Carlyle Group]]'' and Yunfeng Capital.<ref>https://www.carlyle.com/our-business/portfolio-of-investments/gdc-technology-limited</ref><ref>https://www.carlyle.com/media-room/news-release-archive/carlyle-led-consortium-acquires-80-stake-gdc-technology</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/carlyle-cinema-idUKL3E7LH0CC20111017?type=companyNews</ref>\n\n==Artists==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Angelababy]]\n*[[Duan Yihong]]\n*[[Fei (singer)|Fei]]\n*[[Feng Shaofeng]]\n*[[Pace Wu]]\n*[[Li Bing Bing]]\n*[[Lu Ning]] \n*[[He Zhuoyan]]\n*[[Zhao Liying]] \n*[[Zhou Xun]]\n*[[Yao Chen]]\n*[[Wang Luoyong]]\n*[[Vision Wei Chen]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Productions==\n===TV series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! English Title\n! Alternative Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Episodes\n|-\n|2006\n| ''Soldiers Sortie''\n| \u58eb\u5175\u7a81\u51fb\n| 28\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''My Chief and My Regiment''\n| \u6211\u7684\u56e2\u957f\u6211\u7684\u56e2\n| 43\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Dwelling Narrowness'' \n| \u8717\u5c45\n| 35\n|-\n|2010\n| ''Legends of the message''\n| \u98ce\u58f0\u4f20\u5947\n| 30\n|-\n|2011\n| ''Chasing'' or ''Pursuit''\n| \u8ffd\u9003\n| 30\n|-\n|2012\n| ''Husband and Wife''\n| \u592b\u59bb\u90a3\u4e9b\u4e8b\n| 34\n|-\n|2013\n| ''The Heart Without Thieves''\n| \u65e0\u8d3c\n| 48\n|-\n|2018\n| ''Long time no see''\n| \u597d\u4e45\u4e0d